column1: On 30 March 2018, how many GitHub forks will Baidu's Apollo autonomous driving software have?
column5: [' Less than 1,750', 'Between 1,750 and 2,000, inclusive', 'Between 2,001 and 3,000, inclusive', 'More than 3,000 ']
column6: ['Technology']
column11: In July 2017, the Chinese web services company Baidu released "Apollo," an open source autonomous driving operating system (Apollo, Fossbytes). Apollo is available on a GitHub repository, where developers can download the code, modify it, and suggest changes to Baidu. Developers who want to contribute to the Apollo source code must "fork" the repository. For more information on GitHub "forks," visit GitHub's tutorial on the topic. This question will be resolved using Apollo's GitHub repository, which provides an ongoing tally of "forks" in the top right corner. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help. This question closed as "c) Between 2,001 and 3,000 inclusive" with an end date of 30 March 2018. See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

As of October 10, 2017: 1,272 forks - the greatest amount of interest in Baidu Apollo coincided with the Apollo 1.0.0 release https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?q=baidu%20apollo - contributors must fork the repository to contribute changes to the master branch - the number of GitHub commits has steadily declined since release: https://github.com/ApolloAuto/apollo/graphs/contributors?from=2017-07-02&to=2017-10-09&type=c - assumptions: 1) most forks are done by programmers who intend to contribute as opposed to observers (fork vs watch features on GitHub) 2) active contributors do not need to fork a large project very often - unless they are contributing to a fast-changing section of the project, contributors are less likely to need new forks (can develop independently for longer periods with older forks) 3) if the number of GitHub commits per time period are declining, then the number of new forks over the same time period are also declining.

Starting rather flat. It is an interesting topic and I'd expect it to get some traction in the coming month. 2-3k forks is a lot and it strongly depends on the "long tail" of hardly contributing people. I.e. if even a handful of universities use it in a course this winter term this could add a thousand forks or only a handful, depending on how they organise it. We'll have to see how it looks in November

3,000+ forks is quite a lot, unlikely there will be so many people wishing to "modify it, and suggest changes" in given timeframe, but as forking is often used instead of cloning to have a local copy, students and just curious minds can drive the number up. Especially as they already have 1,107 in just 2 months.

My thinking is that the outcome to this question will be determined by participation -- or lack thereof -- in academia. If you look at some of the most forked repositories, a few of them are required for coursework on places like Coursera. Baidu has said it wants to partner with universities, and if that happens it could really move the needle. But without lots of academic participation, I don't see this number moving too dramatically. Thoughts??
